# React & Framework Error/Suspense Boundaries

When generating or modifying React applications (including Next.js, React Router, or standard SPAs):

## Core Rules

- Prefer granular Suspense boundaries around async, data-fetching components to support streaming UI.
- Do not make Suspense boundaries more granular than the intended visual loading sequence.
- Always pair a data-fetching Suspense boundary with an adjacent Error Boundary so localized failures do not crash the full tree.
- Use route-level blocking boundaries only when the entire page layout depends on a single blocking fetch.

## Framework Guidance

- Standard React / React Router:
  - Explicitly wrap with `ErrorBoundary` and `Suspense`.
  - If using React Router deferred loaders, render `<Await>` inside `Suspense`.
- Next.js App Router:
  - Use `loading.tsx` and `error.tsx` only for route-segment-level fallbacks.
  - `error.tsx` must include `"use client"`.
  - Keep inline `Suspense` in `page.tsx` for granular component streaming.

## Example Pattern

```tsx
<ErrorBoundary fallback={<WidgetErrorFallback />}>
  <Suspense fallback={<WidgetSkeleton />}>
    <AsyncWidget />
  </Suspense>
</ErrorBoundary>
```
